<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is MRR and how is it calculated?", answer: "MRR (Monthly Recurring Revenue) is the total predictable revenue your business earns each month from active subscriptions. It is calculated by summing the monthly subscription fees of all paying customers. For annual plans, divide the annual fee by 12. MRR is the fundamental building block for all SaaS financial metrics." },
  { question: "What is a good churn rate for SaaS?", answer: "A good monthly churn rate for SaaS companies is 3-5% for SMB-focused products and under 1% for enterprise SaaS. Annual churn below 10% is considered excellent. Negative net revenue churn, where expansion revenue from existing customers exceeds lost revenue from churned customers, is the gold standard." },
  { question: "How is Customer Lifetime Value (LTV) calculated?", answer: "LTV is calculated as ARPU (Average Revenue Per User) divided by the monthly churn rate. For example, if ARPU is $100/month and monthly churn is 5%, LTV = $100 / 0.05 = $2,000. This represents the total revenue you can expect from an average customer over their entire relationship with your business." },
  { question: "What is a good LTV to CAC ratio?", answer: "The benchmark LTV:CAC ratio is 3:1 or higher, meaning customers generate three times more revenue than the cost to acquire them. Below 1:1 means you are losing money on each customer. Between 1:1 and 3:1 suggests room for improvement. Above 5:1 may indicate underinvestment in growth." },
  { question: "What is the SaaS quick ratio?", answer: "The SaaS quick ratio measures growth efficiency by dividing new MRR (from new and expansion customers) by lost MRR (from churned and contracted customers). A quick ratio above 4x indicates healthy growth. Between 2-4x is acceptable. Below 2x suggests the business is struggling to outpace churn." }
]) %>

